00:21:03.908 --> 00:21:09.308
Nobody could have lasted that long in the freezing temperatures, and all it found

00:21:09.438 --> 00:21:13.948
was the Carpathia rescuing the lucky few who had managed to get on a lifeboat.

00:21:15.188 --> 00:21:21.558
Perhaps surprisingly, no one knows the exact figures of how many people died on the early

00:21:21.558 --> 00:21:30.108
morning of April 15th, but it’s estimated that there were 703 survivors and 1503 deaths.

00:21:31.378 --> 00:21:34.658
And unfortunately, how much you paid for your ticket

00:21:34.898 --> 00:21:38.498
had a large impact on how likely you were to survive.

00:21:39.708 --> 00:21:44.418
Some 61% of the first-class passengers survived, whereas

00:21:44.588 --> 00:21:48.608
less than 25% of third-class passengers survived.

00:21:49.508 --> 00:21:54.328
The evacuation deck was only accessible at first to upper class

00:21:54.328 --> 00:21:58.328
guests so poorer passengers were disproportionately affected.

00:21:59.328 --> 00:22:05.278
There were also reports of bribery, like the so-called ‘Money Boat’, where it was alleged that

00:22:05.278 --> 00:22:11.168
wealthy guests paid the lifeboat crew to sail away even though there was space for more people.

00:22:12.338 --> 00:22:15.218
Another reason that deaths were higher among third

00:22:15.218 --> 00:22:18.378
class passengers was that there were more families.

00:22:19.248 --> 00:22:23.218
When you consider the ‘men saved last’ policy, it’s important

00:22:23.228 --> 00:22:27.248
to underline that boys as young as 13 were considered men.

00:22:28.058 --> 00:22:34.368
As a result, mothers refused to leave their sons behind and countless families died together.

00:22:35.588 --> 00:22:39.128
As news of the disaster spread, the world was shocked.

00:22:39.858 --> 00:22:43.768
Within days, both British and American investigations were launched.

00:22:44.328 --> 00:22:48.868
Death tolls like this were extremely rare, and with so many

00:22:48.968 --> 00:22:53.038
wealthy passengers on board, powerful people wanted answers.

00:22:53.968 --> 00:22:56.138
So, what were the findings?

00:22:56.308 --> 00:22:59.158
Who is to blame, if anyone at all?

00:23:00.008 --> 00:23:04.378
This is the subject of much historical debate but by and large,

00:23:04.648 --> 00:23:09.508
it was considered to be just terrible misfortune, it was bad luck.

00:23:10.758 --> 00:23:14.738
No serious errors were found to have been made by the late Captain

00:23:14.738 --> 00:23:18.958
Smith, and the Titanic was on the correct course the entire time.

00:23:20.348 --> 00:23:24.778
More contemporary analysis shows that the North Atlantic Ocean was

00:23:24.848 --> 00:23:29.638
unusually icy at this time, which created strange weather conditions.

00:23:30.748 --> 00:23:35.398
Without getting too technical, these unusual conditions created something

00:23:35.398 --> 00:23:40.828
called, ‘abnormal refraction’ which causes light to bend unexpectedly.

00:23:41.748 --> 00:23:45.608
Visibility would have been far worse than it actually appeared

00:23:45.618 --> 00:23:50.348
to be, so the ship was only able to see the iceberg far too late.

00:23:51.808 --> 00:24:00.288
Also, whilst turning away from the iceberg seems like the best decision, peculiarly, a full-frontal

00:24:00.318 --> 00:24:06.768
impact, hitting the iceberg directly without changing course would likely have saved the ship.

00:24:07.718 --> 00:24:13.008
A Titanic architect gave evidence and said that in the event of crashing

00:24:13.018 --> 00:24:17.248
directly into the ice, the front of the ship would have crumpled,

00:24:17.438 --> 00:24:22.198
killing around 40 firemen, but the rest would have held intact.

00:24:23.038 --> 00:24:29.148
It has to be said, however, that the other side of the debate judges those involved more harshly.

00:24:30.108 --> 00:24:36.078
Airtight areas weren’t completely sealed, which meant watertight compartments were anything but.

00:24:37.203 --> 00:24:42.288
Also, the steel and iron of the hull, of the bottom of the ship, were weakened

00:24:42.338 --> 00:24:47.218
by the freezing temperatures and speed of travel, which caused the rivets, the

00:24:47.398 --> 00:24:53.948
screws, to pop out easily, which massively sped up the speed at which the ship sank.

00:24:54.818 --> 00:24:59.488
And we can’t forget the crucial fact that no one had the key to the binoculars.

00:25:00.288 --> 00:25:03.738
Could spotting it seconds earlier have made all the difference?

00:25:04.218 --> 00:25:07.678
The story is filled with many agonising ‘what ifs?’.

00:25:08.988 --> 00:25:13.708
In terms of the legacy of the Titanic, to this day it remains one

00:25:13.738 --> 00:25:18.288
of the worst peacetime maritime disasters, in terms of loss of life.

00:25:19.288 --> 00:25:24.188
In the immediate aftermath, there were regulations that required all ships to have

00:25:24.188 --> 00:25:29.968
wireless equipment and crucially, there had to be a ‘lifeboat for every soul’ on board.

00:25:31.151 --> 00:25:34.821
And as to the question of where the Titanic is now, the

00:25:34.821 --> 00:25:38.301
ship still sits at the bottom of the Atlantic Ocean.

00:25:39.451 --> 00:25:44.201
Her wreck was discovered in 1985, but experts say that

00:25:44.211 --> 00:25:48.051
bringing it 4km to the surface would be impossible.

00:25:49.161 --> 00:25:53.621
What’s more, due to rust and water pressure, what remains

00:25:53.641 --> 00:25:57.481
of the ship will likely disintegrate within 30 years.

00:25:58.621 --> 00:26:04.211
So, while the physical remains of the ship will not be around for much longer, the tragic

00:26:04.211 --> 00:26:10.271
story of the Titanic will remain forever, a powerful reminder of the dangers of human pride,

00:26:10.724 --> 00:26:16.481
of the limits of engineering, or perhaps, simply of the immense power of mother nature.

